[1] Comment regarding long-term sequelae
Date: Sun 13 Mar 2016
From: Brett Sutton <drbsutton@gmail.com> [edited]


Regarding PRO/AH/EDR> Ebola update (22): long-term sequelae, news, the research reported by the American Association of Neurologists is very important and timely. It also highlights the critical need for further research.

Although there are clearly objective signs of persistent neurological sequelae in some patients (how many is not quantified in the post), it is notable that the commonest reported symptoms (in a majority of patients) have significant overlap with those associated with post-traumatic stress disorder [PTSD]. It would be of great value if a specific study investigating the prevalence of PTSD could be undertaken. Such symptoms and signs as insomnia, anxiety, hypervigilance, avoidance, nightmares and Impact of Events Scale (IES) might help to clarify whether some of the reported neurological symptoms may in fact be those of PTSD. Reports of a prevalence of PTSD up to at least 25% for survivors of an ICU admission or critical illness have been reported. See: http://hopkinsmedicine.org/news/media/releases/ptsd_common_in_icu_survivors.

In addition, the stressors of home quarantine, widespread fear, ostracism as well as family and community deaths are all likely to play a role in contributing to PTSD. Research into PTSD in West African Ebola survivors would be extremely useful in determining strategies to help prevent or reduce psychological sequelae should another Ebola or similar epidemic ever tragically occur.

--
Dr. Brett Sutton, MBBS, MPHTM
Public Health Registrar,
Centre for Population Health, Burnet Institute, Melbourne, Victoria
<drbsutton@gmail.com>

[ProMED thanks Dr. Sutton for his comment raising the possibility of post-traumatic stress disorder as the cause for the neurologic symptoms observed in Ebola virus disease survivors. He raises a possible alternative explanation for the long-term sequelae. Certainly, research needs to be conducted to clarify causation of these persisting health problems following recovery from Ebola virus disease, and causes other than the virus itself must be considered. - Mod.LK]

