[3] News, NGO, Research
16 Mar 2016 Liberia: As Ebola wanes, a spike in infectious diseases sweeps through Liberia.
http://www.statnews.com/2016/03/16/liberia-tuberculosis-after-ebola/
[The impact of the Ebola virus disease (EVD) epidemic can be seen at health clinics in Liberia: running water is sporadic, drugs are in short supply, and the medical system is still struggling. In addition, Liberia is now recording a spike in cases of tuberculosis and other treatable infections. In this setting, health facilities' ability to deal with treatable diseases, such as tuberculosis, is compromised.
Citation.
Parpia AS, Ndeffo Mbah ML, Wenzel NS, et al. (March 2016). Effects of response to the 2014-2015 Ebola outbreak on deaths from malaria, HIV, and tuberculosis, West Africa. _Emerg Infect Dis_. http://dx.doi.org/10.3201/eid2203.150977

Non-government organization (NGO)
----------------------------------------
March 2016 WHO: Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone "effectively managing" Ebola flare-ups
http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/managing-flare-ups/en/
[EXCERPT:
..."WHO [World Health Organization] believes that all original chains of transmission in the epidemic have been halted, but it continues to stress that small flare-ups are anticipated due to virus persistence in the fluids and tissues of some survivors. While the risk is declining as the virus clears from survivors, it still necessitates a strong surveillance and response capacity, including the ability to detect new and suspect cases, rapid diagnosis, case isolation and management, contact tracing, community awareness and participation, safe burials and care, counseling and screening for survivors." ...more]

Research
------
15 Mar 2016 Russia: Ebola treatment medication developed in Russia -- Ministry of Healthcare http://tass.ru/en/society/862427
[A medication for treating the Ebola [virus disease] has been developed in Russia; the research will be completed in the near future, Russian Healthcare Minister Veronika Skvortsova told reporters on Tue [15 Mar 2016].

"At the preliminary stages, it shows a very high efficiency, making it possible to interrupt the infection process and, consequently, improve the survival rate of the primates that have been infected with Ebola," she said...-more]

[It would be good to see the animal testing data. - Mod.LK]
[When will Phase I human trials begin? - Mod.JW]

15 Mar 2016 UK: Tiny fluorescent crystals help Leeds University scientists understand spread of HIV and Ebola viruses
http://bit.ly/1QYECWa
["Excerpt:
Scientists have used tiny fluorescent crystals to observe for the 1st time how HIV and Ebola viruses attach to cells to spread infection. The findings offer a new way of treating such viruses: instead of destroying the pathogens, [they might] introduce a block on how they interact with cells."

"'Lead author Dr Yuan Guo, from Leeds University's Astbury Centre for Structural Molecular Biology said: "Until now, how these viruses attach to cells was a 'black box' to chemists. We knew that the viruses were interacting with healthy cells, but the way in which they bound together was still a mystery.'"

The researchers used nano-sized crystals, about a millionth of a mm in size, called 'quantum dots,' that mimicked the shape of the viruses and acted as technological stand-ins in experiments to reveal how they bind to cells.]

[Compiled by: Celeste Whitlow <whitlow.celeste@gmail.com>]

